<TD COLSPAN="2"><DIV ALIGN="LEFT"><P><TEXTAREA ROWS="10" NAME="Text" COLS="60">&gt; chao legend, i went through the same
&gt; problem. sorry, but i can only tell you
&gt; 2 things:
&gt; 
&gt; 1.  certain ISP's may be incompatible
&gt;     with any DC, especially AOL, Prodigy,
&gt;     CompuServe, Juno, and NetZero,
&gt;     probably because those are
&gt;     not PPP-compatible.
&gt;     (PPP means point-to-point protocol;
&gt;     AT&amp;T andMSN are 2 examples.)
&gt; 
&gt; 2.  check your phone number options,
&gt;     like your area code, long distance
&gt;     number, and outside number. my advice
&gt;     is to only fill in the dial-up number
&gt;     (you don't need a backup number) and
&gt;     the area code, and the DMP numbers.
&gt;     if you don't know the DMP numbers,
&gt;     write to your ISP about them.
&gt; 
&gt; one last thing: when your PC's connected
&gt; to the Internet, look for the connection
&gt; icon (2 green monitors hooked together),
&gt; right-click on it, and choose Properties.
&gt; this should tell you whether your ISP 
&gt; is PPP compatible or not.
&gt; 
&gt; well, thats all i know. i hope you can
&gt; solve your problem soon!
&gt; 
&gt; 
